# Process Monitoring

One of the most important SOC activities.

Every executable running on Windows creates a process.

Examples:

```text
chrome.exe
powershell.exe
cmd.exe
explorer.exe
svchost.exe
notepad.exe
```

Analysts monitor:

* New processes
* Suspicious processes
* Hidden processes
* Malicious process chains

---

# Process ID (PID)

Every process receives a unique Process ID.

Example:

```text
Process Name : powershell.exe

PID : 4872
```

SOC analysts use PID values to:

* Track execution
* Correlate events
* Investigate attacks

---

# Parent Process and Child Process

Every process originates from another process.

Example:

```text
explorer.exe
     ↓
cmd.exe
     ↓
powershell.exe
```

### Parent Process

The process that launches another process.

### Child Process

The process created by the parent.

---

# Why Parent-Child Analysis Matters

Attackers often abuse trusted applications.

Example:

```text
winword.exe
     ↓
powershell.exe
```

Normal:

```text
explorer.exe
    ↓
notepad.exe
```

Suspicious:

```text
winword.exe
    ↓
powershell.exe
```

This may indicate:

* Malicious macro
* Malware infection
* Initial access attack

